IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: THE WISCONSIN HUMANITIES COUNCIL AWARDS GRANTS TO SUPPORT PROGRAMS IN LIBRARIES, MUSEUMS, UNIVERSITIES, HISTORICAL SOCIETIES, SCHOOLS, AND OTHER NONPROFIT SETTINGS THROUGHOUT THE STATE. THE WISCONSIN HUMANITIES COUNCIL ALSO CREATES PROGRAMS, PARTNERSHIPS, AND PUBLICATIONS TO FULFILL ITS MISSION. THESE PROGRAMS INCLUDE THE COMMUNITY POWERED PROJECT AND A PERIODIC PUBLICATION CALLED "ON."
IRS990.MissionDesc: WISCONSIN HUMANITIES STRENGTHENS OUR DEMOCRACY THROUGH EDUCATIONAL AND CULTURAL PROGRAMS THAT BUILD CONNECTIONS AND UNDERSTANDING AMONG PEOPLE OF ALL BACKGROUNDS AND BELIEFS THROUGHOUT THE STATE.
IRS990.Desc: GRANT PROGRAM - THE WHC'S GRANT PROGRAM PROVIDES SUPPORT FOR PUBLIC HUMANITIES PROGRAMS THAT STRENGTHENS OUR DEMOCRACY THROUGH EDUCATIONAL AND CULTURAL PROGRAMS THAT BUILD CONNECTIONS AND UNDERSTANDING AMONG PEOPLE OF ALL BACKGROUNDS AND BELIEFS THROUGHOUT THE STATE. GRANTS ARE OFFERED THROUGHOUT THE YEAR TO SUPPORT LOCALLY INITIATED PUBLIC HUMANITIES PROGRAMS THAT PROMOTE REFLECTION, DIALOGUE, AND CIVIC PARTICIPATION.FOR THIS TAX YEAR, 35 NEW GRANTS WERE AWARDED. THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY 250 GRANT RELATED EVENTS FUNDED, WITH A TOTAL AUDIENCE OF MORE THAN 57,000 PEOPLE THIS PAST YEAR. IN ADDITION, WITH FUNDING PROVIDED BY THE NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR THE HUMANITIES AS PART OF THE AMERICAN RESCUE PLAN ACT OF 2021, THE WHC PROVIDED GRANT FUNDING TO NONPROFIT HUMANITIES AND CULTURAL ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROVIDE HUMANITIES PROGRAMMING AS A SIGNIFICANT PART OF THEIR MISSION, TO HELP THEM "PREVENT, PREPARE FOR, RESPOND TO, AND RECOVER" FROM THE COVID-19 PANDEMIC. A TOTAL OF 47 GRANTS WERE AWARDED IN TAX YEAR 2021 AND SUCCESSFUL GRANT APPLICANTS HAD RECEIVED $312,354 IN GRANT FUNDS BY THE END OF THE TAX YEAR.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: COMMUNITY POWERED PROJECT PROGRAM- THE COMMUNITY POWERED PROGRAM LAUNCHED AS A PILOT IN FALL OF 2021, BUILDS RESILIENCE AMONG WISCONSIN COMMUNITIES BY HELPING THEM RECOGNIZE, COMMUNICATE, AND ACT UPON THEIR STRENGTHS, CHALLENGES, AND HISTORIES TO ENVISION A VIBRANT FUTURE. RESIDENTS OF 4 PARTICIPATING COMMUNITIES WILL EXPERIENCE NEW WAYS TO UNEARTH AND TELL STORIES OF THEIR COMMUNITIES AND WILL TAKE CONCRETE STEPS TOWARD MAKING THEIR HOMETOWNS EVEN BETTER PLACES TO LIVE. INITIAL PROGRAMMING INCLUDED HIRING AND TRAINING OF FOUR RECENT COLLEGE GRADUATES AND PAIRING THEM WITH LOCAL LIBRARIANS IN THEIR RESPECTIVE HOMETOWN COMMUNITIES OF APPLETON, RACINE, SPOONER, AND THE FOREST COUNTY POTAWATOMI TRIBAL COMMUNITY. WITH THE LIBRARY SERVING AS THE ANCHOR ORGANIZATION, THESE YOUNG PEOPLE AND THEIR LIBRARIAN PARTNERS HAVE BEEN TRAINED IN HUMANITIES AND DIGITAL MEDIA SKILLS AND WILL BE SUPPORTED AS THEY COLLABORATE WITH LOCAL NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS, BUSINESSES, AND CITIZENS TO CREATE LOCALLY MEANINGFUL PROJECTS. AT THE END OF THIS TAX YEAR, 18 HISTORY HARVEST, INTERVIEWING AND OTHER ASSET-MAPPING EVENTS HAVE TAKEN PLACE, WITH A TOTAL OF 475 PEOPLE PARTICIPATING. MAJOR PROGRAMMING WILL TAKE PLACE IN THE SPRING OF 2023.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: LOVE WISCONSIN PROJECT - THE LOVE WISCONSIN PROJECT "CELEBRATES OUR STATE, OUR LIVES AND OUR SHARED FUTURE" VIA A DIGITAL STORYTELLING PROJECT FOCUSED PRIMARILY ON FACEBOOK, USING THE FACEBOOK GROUPS PLATFORM. THIS PLATFORM HAS CREATED AN ONLINE COMMUNITY THAT STRIVES TO BRING ABOUT A MORE CONNECTED, COMPASSIONATE, AND ENGAGED WISCONSIN. THIS PAST YEAR, 47 STORIES HAVE BEEN SHARED, ALONG WITH HUNDREDS OF INSTAGRAM POSTS AND TIKTOK VIDEOS PRODUCED, AND OVER 640,000 PEOPLE REACHED, RESULTING IN NUMEROUS DIGITAL CONVERSATIONS INVOLVING THOUSANDS OF PARTICIPANTS.

ProgSrvcAccomActyOtherGrp.Desc: IMMIGRANT JOURNEYS PROJECT - PROGRAMMING INCLUDED A TRAVELLING EXHIBIT TITLED "IMMIGRANT JOURNEYS FROM SOUTH OF THE BORDER" SHOWCASING THE STORIES OF PEOPLE WHO HAVE IMMIGRATED TO WISCONSIN FROM COLOMBIA, HONDURAS, MEXICO AND URUGUAY, AND A WEBSITE DEDICATED TO THE PROGRAM. IN TAX YEAR 2021, THE EXHIBIT TRAVELED TO 8 SITES IN THE STATE OF WISCONSIN, AND OVER 3,500 PEOPLE VIEWED THE EXHIBIT.

PODCAST PROJECT - "HUMAN POWERED" IS A PODCAST SERIES ABOUT HOW PEOPLE MAKE PLACES BETTER. IT'S ABOUT WHAT CAN HAPPEN WHEN PASSIONATE, CREATIVE PEOPLE ENGAGE DEEPLY WITH THEIR NEIGHBORS AND FIND WAYS TO STRENGTHEN THE ROOTS OF COMMUNITY LIVES. OVER 20,000 PEOPLE LISTENED TO THE SIX PODCASTS THAT WERE PRODUCED IN THE FIRST SEASON OF THE PROGRAM, AND SECOND SEASON OF SIX EPISODES WILL DEBUT IN THE EARLY PART OF TAX YEAR 2023.

"BEYOND THE HEADLINES" PROJECT - "BEYOND THE HEADLINES" IS AN INITIATIVE THAT SEEKS TO DEEPEN THE PUBLIC'S UNDERSTANDING AND APPRECIATION OF THE VITAL CONNECTIONS BETWEEN DEMOCRACY, THE HUMANITIES, JOURNALISM, AND AN INFORMED CITIZENRY. THIS PROGRAM IS PART OF THE "DEMOCRACY AND THE INFORMED CITIZEN" INITIATIVE, ADMINISTERED BY THE FEDERATION OF STATE HUMANITIES COUNCILS, WITH FUNDS FROM THE ANDREW W. MELLON FOUNDATION. IN THE FINAL YEAR OF THIS PROJECT, THERE WERE 4 LIVE EVENTS WITH 541 PARTICIPANTS, AND MORE THAN 20,000 WHO VIEWED OR LISTENED TO THE RECORDED CONTENT FROM THOSE EVENTS ONLINE OR VIA RADIO BROADCASTS, AND 10,000 WHO VIEWED PUBLISHED BTH CONTENT VIA A DOOR COUNTY PERIODICAL.

PROGRAM PARTNERSHIP - IN ADDITION TO ITS OWN PROGRAMMING, THE WHC PROVIDES FINANCIAL SUPPORT OUTSIDE OF THE GRANT PROGRAM FOR HUMANITIES PROGRAMING BY PARTNER ORGANIZATIONS IN THE STATE OF WISCONSIN. THIS YEAR THE WHC CONTINUED ITS PARTNERSHIP WITH WISCONSIN PUBLIC RADIO AND "WISCONSIN LIFE" RADIO PROGRAMMING, AIRING RADIO ESSAYS THAT CELEBRATE WHAT MAKES WISCONSIN UNIQUE THROUGH THE DIVERSE STORIES OF ITS PEOPLE, WITH APPROXIMATELY 70,000 RADIO LISTENERS PER WEEK. THE WHC ALSO CONTINUED ITS SUPPORT OF THE WISCONSIN POET LAUREATE COMMISSION AND THE WISCONSIN POET LAUREATE, THE STATE'S AMBASSADOR FOR POETRY. THE WHC IS ONE OF SIX MEMBER ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROVIDE FINANCIAL SUPPORT AND REPRESENTATIVES TO SERVE ON THE POET LAUREATE COMMISSION.

WILLIAM A. WENNINGER FUND FOR THE PUBLIC HUMANITIES - THESE GRANT FUNDS SUPPORT WHC-FUNDED PROGRAMMING THAT SERVES CHILDREN AND FAMILIES ACROSS WISCONSIN, WITH PRIORITY GIVEN TO PROGRAMMING THAT SERVES NORTHERN WISCONSIN.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION'S LOBBYING ACTIVITIES CONSIST OF ADVOCATING TO LEGISLATORS FOR INCREASED SUPPORT OF HUMANITIES PROGRAMMING IN WISCONSIN.

THE PURPOSE OF THE WENNINGER ENDOWMENT FUND, SET UP WITH THE UW-FOUNDATION IN SEPTEMBER OF 2002, IS TO SUPPORT WHC-FUNDED PROGRAMMING THAT SERVES CHILDREN AND FAMILIES ACROSS WISCONSIN, WITH PRIORITY GIVEN TO PROGRAMMING THAT SERVES NORTHERN WISCONSIN. INTEREST INCOME FROM THIS ENDOWMENT IS TO BE USED EXCLUSIVELY ON THESE TYPES OF PROJECTS AND PROGRAMMING. THE PURPOSE OF THE WISCONSIN HUMANITIES FUTURE FUND IS TO PROVIDE FUNDS THAT WILL BE USED, AT THE DISCRETION OF THE UNIT'S EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR OR THE DIRECTOR'S DESIGNEE, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE UNIT'S BOARD OF DIRECTORS, TO SUPPORT THE UNIT'S MISSION AND OBJECTIVES.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE WISCONSIN HUMANITIES COUNCIL ARRANGES FOR AN EVALUATION OF MANY MAJOR GRANTS AND SELECTED MINI-GRANTS. THESE EVALUATIONS ARE CONDUCTED BY THE ORGANIZATION'S STAFF, MEMBERS OF THE GOVERNING BODY, OR OUTSIDE EVALUATORS. STAFF MAY SHARE THE RESULTS OF THIS EVALUATION WITH THE PROJECT DIRECTOR AND WITH THE DIRECTORS. GRANT RECIPIENTS ARE ASKED TO SEND A FINAL FINANCIAL AND PROGRAM REPORT TO THE ORGANIZATION WITHIN 90 DAYS OF THE END OF THE PROJECT PERIOD. FOR THE PROGRAM REPORT, THE ORGANIZATION REQUESTS A SUMMARY OF ANY INFORMATION OBTAINED THROUGH AUDIENCE QUESTIONNAIRES, ANY SIGNIFICANT WRITTEN COMMENTS RECEIVED FROM PARTICIPANTS, AND COPIES OF ANY PRESS COVERAGE THAT THE PROJECT RECEIVED.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION A, LINE 3
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION'S EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR AND ASSOCIATE DIRECTOR ARE EMPLOYEES OF THE UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN- SYSTEM ADMINISTRATION AND PERFORM MANAGEMENT DUTIES SUCH AS SUPERVISING PERSONNEL, PLANNING AND EXECUTING BUDGETS AND FINANCIAL OPERATIONS, AND SUPERVISING EXEMPT OPERATIONS. DURING CALENDAR YEAR 2021, THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR RECEIVED $93,800 OF REPORTABLE COMPENSATION AND $33,005 OF OTHER COMPENSATION AND THE ASSOCIATE DIRECTOR RECEIVED $70,352 OF REPORTABLE COMPENSATION AND $24,019 OF OTHER COMPENSATION FROM THE UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN- SYSTEM ADMINISTRATION.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 11B
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE PREPARED FORM 990 IS REVIEWED AND APPROVED BY THE ASSOCIATE DIRECTOR BEFORE THE RETURN IS FILED WITH THE IRS.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 12C
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION'S CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY COVERS ALL OF ITS DIRECTORS AND OFFICERS. ANY DIRECTOR OR OFFICER IS CONSIDERED AN INTERESTED PERSON UNDER THE POLICY. IN CONNECTION WITH ANY ACTUAL OR POSSIBLE CONFLICT OF INTEREST, AN INTERESTED PERSON MUST DISCLOSE THE EXISTENCE OF THE FINANCIAL INTEREST AND BE GIVEN THE OPPORTUNITY TO DISCLOSE ALL MATERIAL FACTS TO THE DIRECTORS CONSIDERING THE PROPOSED TRANSACTION OR ARRANGEMENT. THE INTERESTED PERSON MUST LEAVE THE MEETING OF THE GOVERNING BODY WHILE THE DETERMINATION OF A CONFLICT OF INTEREST IS MADE. THE REMAINING DIRECTORS WILL DECIDE IF A CONFLICT OF INTEREST EXISTS AND WILL VOTE ON THE PROPOSED TRANSACTION OR ARRANGEMENT. THE ORGANIZATION'S DIRECTORS AND OFFICERS DO NOT RECEIVE ANY COMPENSATION ON PROJECTS FUNDED BY THE ORGANIZATION AND MUST RECUSE THEMSELVES FROM THE DELIBERATIONS AND DECISIONS ON GRANT REQUESTS FROM ORGANIZATIONS WITH WHICH THEY ARE AFFILIATED.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 15A
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE PERSONNEL COMMITTEE OF THE GOVERNING BODY ANNUALLY EVALUATES THE PERFORMANCE OF THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR AND SUBMITS A WRITTEN EVALUATION THAT INCLUDES A COMPENSATION RECOMMENDATION TO THE EXECUTIVE COMMITTEE PRIOR TO THE JUNE COUNCIL MEETING. THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR MAY CONFER WITH THE GOVERNING BODY BUT IS ULTIMATELY RESPONSIBLE FOR EVALUATING THE PERFORMANCE OF AND ESTABLISHING COMPENSATION FOR THE REST OF THE ORGANIZATION'S PERSONNEL USING CLEARLY ESTABLISHED POLICIES OUTLINED BY THE UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN SYSTEM, OF WHICH THE ORGANIZATION IS ADMINISTRATIVELY AFFILIATED.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION C, LINE 19
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION MAKES ITS GOVERNING DOCUMENTS, CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY, AND FINANCIAL STATEMENTS AVAILABLE TO THE PUBLIC UPON REQUEST.
